Guard retention and submission hunting

Guard passing via controlling and pinning both legs. Arm in between both legs or scooping both and working on advancing position to pin. 

From bottom, focus on framing neck and shrimping or Kipping out.
Take down: collar tie and wrist grab. Flare the wrist when opponent is mirroring stance and shoot for single leg around the outside and clamb between legs.

Stand up. Fireman's carry.
Wrist or tricep control with outside single leg. Load up on back and roll to left shoulder. Keep head attached and turn into opponent. 

Ground work: side control, break head posture, cup the underhook shoulder and pull opponent off floor onto his side, place elbows on his chest and press down. Shift knees into armpit and transition to other side for far side arm bar

One hour living in two positions. 

Top: intentionally offering a leg to enter guard rather than moving round the outside. The goal wasn’t to pass quickly, but to remove variables, knee to the floor, win inside space, connect to the torso and slow the hips before anything else. Once the hips stop moving, the pass starts to happen more freely. 

Bottom: guard retention first, sweep second, reset if needed. Just trying to manage distance, frames and angles. 

Got caught in a head-and-arm and passed a few times, but felt calm and composed on the bottom, and confident working back to neutral.

NTS: playing guard is hard, keep at it.
